M4A4 vs M4A1 Usage

Analysis of the effect of Valve’s nerf in Tier 1 Matches

VDK Stats

1 Introduction

1.1 Previous Articles

      On the 18th of November, Valve pushed a big update: Dust2 was replaced in the active map pool with Anubis, and the AWP and the M4A1-S were nerfed. Three months and several tournaments have passed since that day, so I thought it was a good momento to reflect on the effect that the patch had on the M4’s usage.


      The initial reaction was fairly uniform: M4A1-S is no longer the biggest fish in the sea. Several articles were published, but one of the most completes can be found in ESPORTS.GG, where @xL_csgo went full in depth analyzing the real impact on the changes in the range and damage of the M4A1-S. After BLAST World Finals 2022, HLTV published an article confirming what everybody expected: “M4A4 has taken over as the preferred choice for the first time since the silenced version received substantial buffs to body damage in September 2021”. All the CS community welcome the new year with one idea in mind: M4A1 is no longer the clear best option, some pros even called the new M4A1 “unplayable”. You can check this really interesting interview video by HLTV if you want to get back in the time and check their initial reactions to the update: video.


      As of today, several more tournaments with the update have been played, and we can get a glance of the real effect it had. Is the M4A1 really “unplayable”? Let’s get freaky!

1.2 Database Information

      For this analysis I have used demos from the following tournaments: BLAST Fall Groups 2022, ESL Pro League Season 16, IEM Rio Major 2022 Challengers Stage, BLAST Fall Finals 2022, BLAST World Finals 2022, BLAST Spring Groups 2023, IEM Katowice Play In 2023 and IEM Katowice 2023. In the last four tournaments, the M4A1 update was implemented. I have not included demos from Dust2 and Anubis, since the main goal of this report is to compare the usage before and after the update. Finally, several demos that were splitted had to be omitted from the analysis. You can check the general distribution of maps in the following table:

2 General Comparative

2.1 Kills per round evolution

      Let’s begin this analysis with the most obvious information: kills per round with each weapon. In the general figure we can observe that in the first tournament after the update, the M4A4 did surpass the M4A1. However, this trend was adjusted in BLAST Premier Spring Groups, were both M4s have almost the same KPR. Moreover, in the two phases of IEM Katowice M4A1 was back on the top. Of course, one could argue that this could be explained due to a different distribution in the maps played, so let’s see if we can spot differences among the 6 maps analyzed.


      Ancient is the only map where the M4A4 was back on top in IEM Katowice, with both weapons having almost the same KPR. This seems to indicate that players consider that they have an advantage on Ancient with the M4A4, maybe related to the issue that Rain pointed in the HLTV interview (“I feel like on Nuke it’s really nice to have the silencer because you can spam the cross smokes and do a lot of damage. I don’t want them to notice where I am all of the time, so that’s why I have it there … On Ancient it’s all close range for me on B site, if you’re spamming they know so it doesn’t really matter. So yeah, it’s map-dependent.”). Mirage and Nuke are two maps were both M4s have almost the same KPR, while Vertigo, Overpass and Inferno seem to favored the M4A1.

2.2 Distance per Kill

      Another question that may arise is: does the increase accuracy of the M4A1-S give an advantage in long distance fights? In the following figures you can check that the average distance of the kills, in units, is almost the same for both M4s. Surely, this means that there is not an advantage in long distance fights. However, if we look at the boxplots in the extreme values section, there is a clear difference: the M4A1 presents way more extremely high values in tournaments before the nerf. After the nerf, it still seems to favour long range duels, but the difference is much smaller.

2.3 Entry kills per weapon

      In this section, we ask ourselves the following question: Is the M4A1 better for entry duels?. One might think that, as the round progress the M4A4 could present advantages over the M4A1, such as the increase damage and the bigger magazine. However, there may be a difference in early round duels that justifies choosing the M4A1 if you are looking for early fights. In the general figure, the M4A1 really seems to be prefered to the M4A4. However, once we make the distinction of pre-nerf vs post-nerf, we can spot a clear change: before the update, the M4A1 really was looking for, and winning, the early duels. After the nerf, not only the percentage of entry kills with the M4A4 increases considerably, all the percentages for the other rifles increase in almost every map. Moreover, the increase in entry kills won by the CT rifles does not cover the loss of the entry kills obtained by the M4A1. One explanation could be that CTs are, in general, losing more early duels to people with Galils, AWPs and AKs.

2.4 Kills through smokes

      Finally, the last question is: Does the lack of tracers of the M4A1 presents a clear advantage when spamming smokes? Let’s look at percentage of kills through smoke and try to answer this question. Pre-nerf the M4A1 was clearly getting more kills through smokes, competing with the AK47 in almost every map. After the update, the M4A1 falls of a cliff and even though the M4A4 gets a higher percentage it does not cover the loss of the M4A1. The biggest beneficiary is the AK-47, which increases the percentage of kills through smokes and, therefore, the T side.

3 Comparison between teams

      There is one final question remaining. But, what about teams? Are all teams using the same approach? Well, they are clearly NOT. In the following figures you can see the KPR per tournament with both M4s for different top tier teams. Some of them are almost at 50/50, like NaVi and Cloud9. Other are coming back to the M4A1 after the initial shock, such as Liquid, Heroic, FaZe and Vitality. Outsiders never really gave a fuck about the update, they have kept using the M4A1. But one team, only one, has fully embraced the M4A4. I think all of us can guess who without even doing this analysis: G2. Could this be one of their reasons of their recent success?

4 Conclusions

      We have dive deep into the differences in usage in the M4A1 and the M4A4 before and after the update. There are several conclusions that we can extract:
  • After the initial shock, most teams have come back to the M4A1.
  • The M4A1 seems to give a slight advantage in extremely high distance duels.
  • The update has nerfed the M4A1 in early duels and kills through smokes, damaging the CT side and favouring the T side.
  • G2 is with clear difference the team that has fully adopted the new M4A4 meta.
